'''George Speake''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} is an English art historian and archaeologist.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} He is an Honorary Research Fellow at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]] at [[Oxford]],{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} and "a leading authority on Anglo-Saxon animal art."{{sfn|Barbican Research}} Currently Speake is the Anglo-Saxon Art and Iconography Specialist for the [[Staffordshire Hoard]] conservation team,{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}} and is working on the reconstruction of the [[Staffordshire helmet]].{{sfn|ICON|2016}}{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}}

==Early life and education==
George Speake was educated at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] in the 1960s, and the [[University of Oxford]], where he studied at [[St John's College, Oxford|St John's College]] and at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]], in the 1970s.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} At Oxford he studied under [[Christopher Hawkes|Christopher]] and Sonia Hawkes, obtaining a [[Ph.D.]] in 1974 with a thesis about [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] animal art.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}}

==Career==
[[File:Staffordshire helmet terminal.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of the horse terminal from the Staffordshire helmet|Horse head terminal from the [[Staffordshire helmet]]]]
Speake specialises in Anglo-Saxon art and iconography.{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=29, 34, 41}} As of 2016 he is working on the reconstruction of the more than 1,000 pieces of the [[Staffordshire helmet]],{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}}{{sfn|ICON|2016}} following work on the [[Royal Saxon tomb in Prittlewell|Prittlewell burial]], and teaching fine art and art history.{{sfn|Barbican Research}} In 2014 he coauthored a book on the [[Staffordshire Hoard]], ''Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard'', identifying among other characteristics an "eyeless, open-jawed serpent" depicted on the helmet's cheek guard.{{sfn|Fern|Speake|2014|p=34}} A paper on the helmet is due to be published in 2018.{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}} He is also an Honorary Research Fellow at the Institute of Archaeology at Oxford.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}

Speake's 1980 work ''Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background'',{{sfn|Speake|1980}} written as the basis for his Ph.D.,{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} is considered "a major break-through in Anglo-Saxon style studies".{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=448}} It provided a comprehensive look at "[[Migration Period art#Animal style|style II]]" art,{{sfn|Hills|1981|p=225}} the form of zoomorphic decoration used in [[Northern Europe]] from the middle of the sixth century AD to the end of the seventh.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} Hitherto the least understood style of Anglo-Saxon and [[Scandinavia]]n animal art,{{sfn|Raw|1981|p=327}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} style II is thought to have been reserved for the upper classes and is found prominently on the objects found in the [[Sutton Hoo]] [[ship burial|ship-burial]] and in the [[Vendel]] boat graves.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=447}}{{sfn|Higgitt|1982|pp=62–63}} Speake's work was credited with discussing every known example of the style through 1974—the date of his Ph.D.—and with proving that it was introduced to England from [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], and [[Sweden]].{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|pp=446–447}}

