'''Greg DePaul''' is an American [[playwright]] and [[screenwriter]], best known for the romantic comedy ''[[Bride Wars]]''.<ref name="wordpress">{{cite web|url=https://screenwritingfromiowa.wordpress.com/2016/09/20/screenwriter-greg-depaul-qa-part-6/|title=Screenwriter Greg DePaul Q&amp;A (Part 6)|website=Screenwriting from Iowa|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref>
==Biography== DePaul grew up in Maryland and graduated from NYU. After college, he worked as a private investigator and wrote for ''[[The Washington Post]]''. In 1998, DePaul moved to Los Angeles, where he directed his own play, ''Motherlove''. DePaul teamed with writer Hank Nelken to create a comic short film, ''Jerry Mashugana'', a parody of the hit comedy ''[[Jerry Maguire]]'', which starred [[Matt Damon]], [[Geoffrey Rush]] and [[Demi Moore]].
==Career== ''[[Saving Silverman]]'', starring [[Jack Black]] and [[Jason Biggs]], which was released by Sony Pictures in 2001. The film falls within a cross-genre film type from the late 1990s and early 2000s in which grooms are saved, or nearly saved, from distasteful marriage.<ref name="Slate">Adam Sternbergh (January 28, 2004). [http://www.slate.com/id/2094507/ "The Devil Wears Pearls: In recent movies, grooms across America flee their frigid fiancees"]. [[Slate Magazine]].</ref> It opened at No. 3 at the North American box office making $7.4&nbsp;million [[USD]] in its opening weekend. The film grossed a domestic total of $19,402,030 and $26,086,706 worldwide from a $22&nbsp;million budget.<ref>{{mojo title|savingsilverman|Saving Silverman}}<!--whole para so far--></ref> ''Killer Bud'', was produced independently. It was [[Robert Stack]]'s final film prior to his death in 2003.
He then wrote ''Bride Wars'', starring Kate Hudson, Anne Hathaway and Candace Bergen. DePaul got the idea when he and his wife were planning a double wedding with her sister.<ref name="scriptmag">{{cite web|url=http://www.scriptmag.com/features/career-features/selling-screenplay-screenwriter-greg-depaul-career-writing-comedy|title=Selling Your Screenplay: Screenwriter Greg DePaul on His Career Writing Comedy - Script Magazine|website=scriptmag.com|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref name="la-screenwriter">{{cite web|url=http://www.la-screenwriter.com/2016/11/28/screenwriter-greg-depaul-on-his-career-as-a-comedy-screenwriter/|title=Screenwriter Greg DePaul On His Career as a Comedy Screenwriter|website=LA Screenwriter|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> In its opening weekend, the film grossed $21,058,173 ranking #2 at the box office.<ref name="BOM">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bridewars.htm |title=Bride Wars (2009) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2009-05-26}}</ref> A Chinese [[remake]] [[Bride Wars (2015 film)|of the same name]] was released in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/bride-wars-review-1201576787/|title= Film Review: ‘Bride Wars’|author= Maggie Lee|date= August 24, 2015|accessdate= 2015-10-10|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref>
DePaul's plays and sketch comedy have been performed by The Collective NY, a theatre company in Manhattan.<ref name="thecollective-ny">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecollective-ny.org/ensemble-2/|title=Our Company|website=The Collective NY|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> He has performed improv comedy and co-founded Cornfed. DePaul has served on the Board of the Writers and Actors Lab, and co-founded The Clark Street Players. He wrote the comedy screenwriting manual, ''Bring the Funny: The Essential Companion for the Comedy Screenwriter''.<ref name="bringthefunny">{{cite web|url=http://www.bringthefunny.com/bring-the-funny.html|title=Bring the funny - Greg DePaul|website=bringthefunny.com|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> He also led a screenwriting workshop for Harvardwood, a group of Harvard alumni in the entertainment industry, and taught Screenwriting at NYU.<ref name="nyu">{{cite web|url=https://www.sps.nyu.edu/professional-pathways/faculty/16309-gregory-depaul.html|title=Faculty Profile: Gregory DePaul, Adjunct Instructor &#124; NYU SPS Professional Pathways|website=sps.nyu.edu|accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref>
