{{Infobox writer | name = Wayne Gladstone | pseudonym = Gladstone | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[United States]] | occupation = [[Humorist]], [[novelist]] | language = [[English language|English]] | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | education = | alma_mater = | period = Contemporary | genre = [[Satire]], [[Utopian and dystopian fiction|dystopian]] | subject = [[Pop culture]], [[news media]], [[Americana]] | movement = | notableworks = ''[[Notes from the Internet Apocalypse]]'' | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|kafkamaine.com}} | portaldisp = }}
'''Wayne Gladstone''' (also known as '''Gladstone''') is an American writer, humorist and novelist perhaps best known for his work with [[Cracked.com]]<ref>{{cite web|title=G-Stone|url=http://www.cracked.com/members/G-Stone/|publisher=[[Cracked.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookreporter.com/authors/wayne-gladstone|title=Wayne Gladstone|publisher=Bookreporter.com}}</ref> and the novel ''[[Notes from the Internet Apocalypse]]'', the first in a trilogy of books entitled ''The Internet Apocalypse Trilogy''.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 4, 2014|title=NOTES FROM THE INTERNET APOCALYPSE: A Novel|url=http://us.macmillan.com/notesfromtheinternetapocalypse/waynegladstone|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Notes from the Internet Apocalypse|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/wayne-gladstone/notes-from-the-internet-apocalypse/|work=[[Kirkus Reviews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[Toronto Star]]|title=Notes From the Internet Apocalypse: Review|author=Dundas, Deborah|date=March 12, 2014|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2014/03/12/notes_from_the_internet_apocalypse_review.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Pop Quiz at the End of the Universe: Wayne Gladstone|date=March 4, 2014|publisher=[[Tor Books]]|url=http://www.tor.com/2014/03/04/the-pop-quiz-at-the-end-of-the-universe-wayne-gladstone/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Is this debut novel from a Cracked writer just trolling its readers?|author=Nelson, Samantha|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/debut-novel-cracked-writer-just-trolling-its-reade-201674|date=March 3, 2014|work=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref>
Following the release of ''Notes from the Internet Apocalypse'', Gladstone has been interviewed on the internet's effect on pop culture by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'',<ref name="What is the Internet Doing To Us Really">{{cite web|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|url=http://www.esquire.com/news-politics/news/a27719/what-is-the-internet-doing-to-us-really/|title=Is The Internet Making Us Dumber, Smarter, Or Just Different?|first=Luke|last=O'Neil|date=March 10, 2014}}</ref> as well as appearing on Fusion.net in an interview hypothesizing the societal effects of the disappearance of the Internet.<ref name="Fusion TV">{{cite video|url=http://fusion.net/video/2075/the-internet-apocalypse-is-it-the-end-of-the-web-as-we-know-it/|publisher=[[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]]|title=The Internet Apocalypse: Is It the End of the Web As We Know It?|author=Lorenzo, Adriana|date=March 18, 2014}}</ref>
The second novel in Gladstone's Internet apocalypse trilogy, ''Agents of the Internet Apocalypse'', was released in July 21, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 21, 2015|title=AGENTS OF THE INTERNET APOCALYPSE: A Novel|url=http://us.macmillan.com/agentsoftheinternetapocalypse/waynegladstone|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]}}</ref>
